 Assistant: Solution : 

To compute the smallest rectangle containing both r1 and r2, we need to find the coordinates of the lower left and upper right corners of the new rectangle. Let's call the new rectangle r3.

The x-coordinate of the lower left corner of r3 will be the minimum of the x-coordinates of r1 and r2. Similarly, the y-coordinate of the lower left corner of r3 will be the minimum of the y-coordinates of r1 and r2.

Therefore, the lower left corner of r3 can be computed as follows:

$x_3 = min(x_1, x_2)$

$y_3 = min(y_1, y_2)$

Similarly, the x-coordinate of the upper right corner of r3 will be the maximum of the x-coordinates of r1 and r2, and the y-coordinate of the upper right corner of r3 will be the maximum of the y-coordinates of r1 and r2.

Therefore, the upper right corner of r3 can be computed as follows:

$x_4 = max(x_1, x_2)$

$y_4 = max(y_1, y_2)$

Finally, we can create the new rectangle r3 with the lower left corner $(x_3, y_3)$ and the upper right corner $(x_4, y_4)$.

The implementation of the hull2 operation in Java would look like this:

public static Rectangle hull2(Rectangle r1, Rectangle r2) {
    long x1 = Math.min(r1.x1, r2.x1);
    long y1 = Math.min(r1.y1, r2.y1);
    long x2 = Math.max(r1.x2, r2.x2);
    long y2 = Math.max(r1.y2, r2.y2);
    return new Rectangle(x1, y1, x2, y2);
}

Note that the Rectangle class is assumed to have four fields x1, y1, x2, and y2 representing the coordinates of the lower left and upper right corners of the rectangle.

